Bribery was powerless to avert a, conviction— much less was it needed to procure one.'' The objection that this statement would never have been made by a prosecutor who is trying to saddle the defence with the bribery scandal, and that it voids the (imaginary) argument of the defendant when he follows with the admission that he had, unlike the prosecutor, every motive to bribe, is apparent rather than real. There is no ground for the inference that the defendant, according to the prosecutor’s own showing, attempted an impossibility. What the prosecutor says is that Oppianicus's guilt was so manifest that bribery would have been of no avail——as it seemed to him—even to avert a conviction. But for all that the defenee, it is alleged, made the attempt.
